    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1964-07-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1964-07-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="344"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d344">
                <head>344. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_KRW1" type="from">Robert W.
                        Komer</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to the Assistant
                    Secretary of State for Far Eastern Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_BWP1"
                        type="to">Bundy</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d344fn1"
                        >Source: Johnson Library, National Security File, Country File, Korea, Vol.
                        II. Confidential.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1964-07-22">July 22, 1964</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Here’s a strong plug for Marshall <persName corresp="#p_GM1">Green</persName>’s
                    idea that we shoot for a limited <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>/Jap
                    normalization, so long as prospects for early agreement on the full package seem
                    limited. I still wonder why the <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>s would
                    settle for so much less, but if Marshall, Embassy Seoul, and <persName
                        corresp="#p_CICI1">Chong Il-kwon</persName> are all interested why not
                    try.</p>
                <p>Marshall mentioned separately to me his idea that as part of the exercise the US
                    would depart from its backstage role to make strong direct approaches,
                    especially to the <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>s. I note that <persName
                        corresp="#p_CICI1">Chong Il-kwon</persName> also wants the US to associate
                    itself publicly with the enterprise. To me, the potential gain is well worth the
                    risk.</p>
                <p>Wouldn’t Win <persName corresp="#p_BWG1">Brown</persName>’s arrival be a good
                    time to spring this one?<note n="2" xml:id="d344fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWG1">Winthrop Brown</persName> was appointed
                        Ambassador to the Republic of Korea on July 31.</note> We could even arm him
                    with some words from the President; we could use a few foreign policy pluses
                    before November, and <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>/Jap normalization might
                    just be made into one.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">
                            <persName corresp="#p_KRW1">R.W. Komer</persName>
                        </hi>
                        <note n="3" xml:id="d344fn3">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
